## Diagnosis

You're right to call this out. This is a classic **documentation drift** anti-pattern (AP-072): implementation outpaces its documentation, and the playground becomes stale the moment a new variant lands. Without a forcing function, every new variant requires a separate feedback loop to get documented.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-072 – Implementation/Documentation Drift**: There is no structural coupling between the component's variant definition and its playground entry. Adding a variant to the component source is a completely independent action from updating the playground, so documentation is perpetually optional-in-practice.

---

## Fix

### 1. Document the `solid` variant in the playground

**File: `src/app/(frontend)/playground/navigation/page.tsx`**

```tsx
import { Navigation } from "@/components/Navigation";

const VARIANTS = ["default", "ghost", "solid"] as const; // ← add "solid"

const NAV_ITEMS = [
  { label: "Home",     href: "/" },
  { label: "Work",     href: "/work" },
  { label: "About",    href: "/about" },
  { label: "Contact",  href: "/contact" },
];

export default function NavigationPlayground() {
  return (
    <main className="space-y-16 p-12">
      <h1 className="text-3xl font-semibold">Navigation — Playground</h1>

      {VARIANTS.map((appearance) => (
        <section key={appearance} className="space-y-4">
          <h2 className="text-sm font-mono uppercase tracking-widest text-neutral-500">
            appearance="{appearance}"
          </h2>

          {/* Default state */}
          <Navigation appearance={appearance} items={NAV_ITEMS} />

          {/* With an active item */}
          <Navigation
            appearance={appearance}
            items={NAV_ITEMS}
            activeHref="/work"
          />
        </section>
      ))}
    </main>
  );
}
```

---

### 2. Add a compile-time exhaustiveness guard in the playground

This makes it **impossible** to ship a new variant without the playground file failing the TypeScript compiler.

**File: `src/app/(frontend)/playground/navigation/page.tsx`** *(add near the top)*

```ts
import type { NavigationAppearance } from "@/components/Navigation";

// ── Exhaustiveness guard ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// If you add a variant to NavigationAppearance without adding it to VARIANTS,
// this line will produce a TypeScript error at build time.
// Do NOT widen this type — fix the playground instead.
const VARIANTS = ["default", "ghost", "solid"] as const;
type _Guard = [NavigationAppearance] extends [typeof VARIANTS[number]]
  ? [typeof VARIANTS[number]] extends [NavigationAppearance]
    ? true
    : never
  : never;
const _exhaust: _Guard = true; // TS error here means a variant is undocumented
// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
```

This is a **bidirectional** check:
- `NavigationAppearance ⊆ VARIANTS[number]` → every defined variant is in the playground.
- `VARIANTS[number] ⊆ NavigationAppearance` → no phantom variants in the playground.

---

### 3. Export the appearance type from the component (required for the guard)

**File: `src/components/Navigation/index.tsx`**

```ts
// Add or confirm this export already exists:
export type NavigationAppearance = "default" | "ghost" | "solid";

interface NavigationProps {
  appearance?: NavigationAppearance;
  items: { label: string; href: string }[];
  activeHref?: string;
}
```

---

### 4. Codify the rule: Variant Covenant

**File: `CONTRIBUTING.md`** *(add section)*

```markdown
## Variant Covenant

Every component that accepts an `appearance` (or equivalent discriminant) prop
MUST satisfy the following **before a PR can merge**:

### Rule VC-1 — Export the union type
The appearance union MUST be exported from the component's entry file:
  `export type <Component>Appearance = "variantA" | "variantB";`

### Rule VC-2 — Exhaust it in the playground
The playground page MUST import that type and include a bidirectional
TypeScript exhaustiveness guard (see template below).
`tsc --noEmit` is run in CI; a new variant that breaks the guard blocks merge.

### Rule VC-3 — One section per variant
Each variant MUST have its own labeled `<section>` in the playground showing
at minimum: default state and one interactive/active state.

### Template
Copy `src/app/(frontend)/playground/_template/page.tsx` when creating a new
playground page. It includes the guard wired up and ready to fill in.

### Checklist (add to PR template)
- [ ] New/changed variant type exported from component
- [ ] Playground `VARIANTS` array updated
- [ ] Exhaustiveness guard passes (`pnpm typecheck`)
- [ ] Visual diff reviewed in playground route
```

---

### 5. Add the playground template

**File: `src/app/(frontend)/playground/_template/page.tsx`**

```tsx
/**
 * Playground template — copy this file when adding a new component playground.
 * Replace every occurrence of `Example` / `ExampleAppearance` with your component.
 */
import { Example } from "@/components/Example";
import type { ExampleAppearance } from "@/components/Example";

const VARIANTS: ExampleAppearance[] = [
  "default",
  // add variants here
];

// Exhaustiveness guard — TS error here means a variant is undocumented.
type _Guard = [ExampleAppearance] extends [typeof VARIANTS[number]]
  ? [typeof VARIANTS[number]] extends [ExampleAppearance]
    ? true
    : never
  : never;
const _exhaust: _Guard = true;

export default function ExamplePlayground() {
  return (
    <main className="space-y-16 p-12">
      <h1 className="text-3xl font-semibold">Example — Playground</h1>
      {VARIANTS.map((appearance) => (
        <section key={appearance} className="space-y-4">
          <h2 className="text-sm font-mono uppercase tracking-widest text-neutral-500">
            appearance="{appearance}"
          </h2>
          <Example appearance={appearance} />
        </section>
      ))}
    </main>
  );
}
```

---

## Principle

> **Variant Covenant (VC)**: A variant that exists only in source code does not exist in the design system. Documentation is not a follow-up task — it is part of the definition of done. Enforce this structurally (TypeScript exhaustiveness guard + CI `typecheck`) so the rule requires zero discipline to follow and costs a compile error to break.

The key insight is the **bidirectional type guard**: it costs two lines of TypeScript and turns a social contract into a compiler error. No linter plugin, no checklist reminder, no code-review note — just a red build.
